│ stop({"edit_points": [[18598, 18614,                                          │
│ "llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp"]], "thoughts": "1.          │
│ Understanding the Issue:\nThe crash is an assertion failure from DenseMap::at │
│ reporting a missing key while vectorizing a horizontal reduction in the SLP   │
│ vectorizer. The failure point is at (anonymous                                │
│ namespace)::HorizontalReduction::tryToReduce(), line 18609, where             │
│ TrackedToOrig.at(RdxVal) is called. This indicates that the DenseMap          │
│ TrackedToOrig does not contain the queried key RdxVal.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's  │
│ Log:\nThe debug log shows the pass schedules and vectorizes a bundle of add   │
│ i16 ... , 0 instructions, then proceeds to erase several scalars.             │
│ Subsequently, the pass continues processing horizontal reductions and         │
│ crashes. Notably, there is a message: \"Need to extract: Extra arg from lane  │
│ 2 from %subi = add i16 0, 0.\" This suggests %subi appears as an extra        │
│ operand in the vectorization tree. The crash stack indicates it happens       │
│ during the \"Gather externally used values\" phase in tryToReduce,            │
│ specifically at line 18609.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nInside tryToReduce,   │
│ we build Candidates and TrackedToOrig mapping as follows:\n- For each         │
│ original reduced value OrigV, we compute a tracked value RdxVal =             │
│ TrackedVals.at(OrigV), and then we push RdxVal into Candidates and insert a   │
│ key/value into TrackedToOrig mapping from that RdxVal (the tracked value at   │
│ build time) to OrigV.\n\nLater, in the \"Gather externally used values\" loop │
│ (lines 18595–18614):\n- We iterate over Candidates with RdxVal =              │
│ Candidates[Cnt].\n- Critically, we then attempt to \"stabilize\" RdxVal by    │
│ doing: if (auto It = TrackedVals.find(RdxVal)) RdxVal = It->second; This      │
│ re-maps RdxVal through TrackedVals if RdxVal is a key there.\n\nThe problem:  │
│ TrackedToOrig is keyed by the tracked value pointer RdxVal as it existed when │
│ the Candidates vector was built. If RdxVal has since been RAUW-replaced (for  │
│ example, add 0,0 simplified to a constant 0) due to earlier transformations,  │
│ TrackedVals (using WeakTrackingVH) may now map the original RdxVal to a       │
│ different, new Value* (like a ConstantInt 0). Thus, the code changes RdxVal   │
│ to a new pointer (the tracked current value), and then performs               │
│ TrackedToOrig.at(RdxVal). But TrackedToOrig is not updated by RAUW since it   │
│ stores raw Value* keys; it still contains the old pointer key, not the new    │
│ one. Therefore, the at() lookup fails, causing the assertion.\n\nIn the       │
│ specific reproducer, RdxVal becomes %subi initially, but (due to earlier      │
│ transforms) TrackedVals may map %subi to constant 0. The code then changes    │
│ RdxVal to 0 and tries TrackedToOrig.at(0), which misses, causing the          │
│ crash.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s)\nEdit file:                               │
│ llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp, lines 18598–18614.\n\nGoal:  │
│ Avoid using the potentially-updated tracked (stable) value as the key for     │
│ TrackedToOrig lookups. We should preserve the original candidate key for      │
│ lookups into TrackedToOrig while still using the stable value for             │
│ external-uses bookkeeping (Visited/LocalExternallyUsedValues and              │
│ checks).\n\nConcrete change:\n- Introduce a separate StableRdxVal variable.   │
│ Keep RdxVal as the original Candidates[Cnt] value for TrackedToOrig.at        │
│ lookups.\n- Use StableRdxVal for Visited, VLScalars.contains, V.isVectorized  │
│ checks, and for adding to LocalExternallyUsedValues.\n\nBefore:\n  Value      │
│ *RdxVal = Candidates[Cnt];\n  if (auto It = TrackedVals.find(RdxVal); It !=   │
│ TrackedVals.end())\n    RdxVal = It->second;\n  if                            │
│ (!Visited.insert(RdxVal).second) continue;\n  if (!VLScalars.contains(RdxVal) │
│ && V.isVectorized(RdxVal)) { ... }\n  Value *OrigV =                          │
│ TrackedToOrig.at(RdxVal);\n  ...\n  if (NumOps !=                             │
│ ReducedValsToOps.at(OrigV).size())\n                                          │
│ LocalExternallyUsedValues[RdxVal];\n\nAfter:\n  Value *RdxVal =               │
│ Candidates[Cnt];           // original candidate key\n  Value *StableRdxVal = │
│ RdxVal;              // may be RAUW-updated value\n  if (auto It =            │
│ TrackedVals.find(RdxVal); It != TrackedVals.end())\n    StableRdxVal =        │
│ It->second;\n  if (!Visited.insert(StableRdxVal).second) continue;\n  if      │
│ (!VLScalars.contains(StableRdxVal) && V.isVectorized(StableRdxVal)) {         │
│ LocalExternallyUsedValues[StableRdxVal]; continue; }\n  Value *OrigV =        │
│ TrackedToOrig.at(RdxVal);   // use original key for map lookup\n  unsigned    │
│ NumOps = VectorizedVals.lookup(OrigV) + At(SameValuesCounter, OrigV);\n  if   │
│ (NumOps != ReducedValsToOps.at(OrigV).size())\n                               │
│ LocalExternallyUsedValues[StableRdxVal];\n\nThis ensures the DenseMap::at     │
│ lookup uses the same key under which the mapping was established and prevents │
│ lookup failure when the tracked value has been RAUW’ed to another             │
│ Value*.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nThe crash occurs because we update RdxVal to a     │
│ RAUW-tracked value before using it as a key in TrackedToOrig, which was       │
│ populated with the pre-RAUW pointer keys. Separating the notion of the        │
│ \"original candidate key\" (for TrackedToOrig lookups) from the \"stable      │
│ current value\" (for external-use tracking) resolves the inconsistency. This  │
│ patch prevents the assertion and correctly handles values that may be         │
│ replaced between analysis/data-structure construction and subsequent scans    │
│ within tryToReduce."})                                                        │
